Two leading betting firms are among four blue chip companies tussling for the Sh200 million worth deal for the naming and branding rights of the Nyayo Nation Stadium.Sunday Nation Sport understands that both SportPesa and Betway have already commenced negotiations with Sports Kenya over the deal. Sports Kenya is the parastatal charged with the management of all the Government owned sports facilities in the country. I can confirm the (naming rights) deals for both Nyayo and Kasarani Stadia expire soon. We are pleased with the interest from our brothers in the corporate in partnering with us on this front," Sports Kenya Director General Gordon Oluoch told Sunday Nation Sport.Financial services group, Britam, whose current two-year naming rights deal for the 30,000-seater Nyayo Stadium lapses in December, are also interested. Meanwhile, giant telecommunications firm Safaricom, who own a similar rights deal at the 60,000-seater Kasarani Stadium, are also said to have expressed interest.Safaricom switched their attention to Nyayo Stadium owing to the "unavailability" of the Kasarani Stadium which is set to host the World Under-18 Athletics Championships next year. It is understood the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) have insisted the competition be held at a stadium with no corporate branding."We are happy to note the financial relationship with our partners on this front helped us renovate and upgrade the two facilities. There is still a lot of work to do to transform the facilities to international standards, and that is why we are seeking to negotiate new deals," Oluoch added. email print email print Mr Menjo says this device can even be concealed from the driver in a PSV. The official organisers of the concert are Walee Wasee Ltd who approached KTB for support.